(72,	0,	1,	20240730,	'ask',	'how to become a PR in Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 13:07:24',	0,	'2024-07-30 13:07:24',	0,	NULL),
(73,	72,	1,	20240730,	'reply',	'**Steps to Become a Public Relations (PR) Practitioner in Australia:**\n\n**1. Obtain a Degree or Diploma:**\n\n* Bachelor&#039;s or Master&#039;s degree in Public Relations, Communications, or a related field from an accredited Australian university.\n* You can also complete a diploma in Public Relations from a reputable vocational education and training (VET) institution.\n\n**2. Gain Practical Experience:**\n\n* Internships, work experience, or volunteer roles in the PR industry are invaluable.\n* Seek opportunities in agencies, corporate organizations, or non-profit sectors.\n\n**3. Join a Professional Association:**\n\n* Membership in the Public Relations Institute of Australia (PRIA) demonstrates your commitment to the profession and provides access to networking and professional development opportunities.\n\n**4. Obtain Certification:**\n\n* The PRIA Certified Public Relations Practitioner (CPRPRP) certification is a recognized industry benchmark.\n* It involves passing a comprehensive exam and demonstrating a minimum of three years of professional experience.\n\n**5. Meet Code of Ethics Standards:**\n\n* Adhere to the PRIA Code of Ethics, which outlines ethical guidelines for PR practitioners in Australia.\n\n**6. Stay Up-to-Date:**\n\n* Continuously update your knowledge and skills through industry events, conferences, and professional development courses.\n\n**7. Build Your Network:**\n\n* Attend PR industry events and connect with professionals in the field.\n* Leverage social media platforms to engage with potential clients and colleagues.\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n* Demonstrate strong communication, writing, and problem-solving skills.\n* Have a deep understanding of social media, digital marketing, and media relations.\n* Be adaptable and able to work in a fast-paced and demanding environment.\n* Seek mentorship from experienced PR professionals.\n\n**Employment Opportunities:**\n\nPR practitioners in Australia can work in various industries, including:\n\n* PR agencies\n* Corporate communications departments\n* Government organizations\n* Non-profit organizations\n* Media outlets',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 13:07:24',	0,	'2024-07-30 13:07:24',	0,	NULL),
(74,	0,	1,	20240730,	'ask',	'how to become permanent resident in Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 13:08:31',	0,	'2024-07-30 13:08:31',	0,	NULL),
(75,	0,	1,	20240730,	'ask',	'how to become a permanent resident in Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 13:09:39',	0,	'2024-07-30 13:09:39',	0,	NULL),
(76,	75,	1,	20240730,	'reply',	'**Pathways to Permanent Residency in Australia**\n\n**1. Skilled Migration**\n\n* Apply for a skilled visa that corresponds to your occupation and skills.\n* Meet minimum points thresholds based on age, education, work experience, and other factors.\n* Secure a nomination from an Australian state or territory government or an employer.\n\n**2. Family Sponsorship**\n\n* Be sponsored by an Australian citizen, permanent resident, or eligible New Zealand citizen.\n* Meet the relationship and financial requirements of the sponsor.\n* Apply for a family visa category, such as Partner Visa or Child Visa.\n\n**3. Business or Investment**\n\n* Establish or invest in a business in Australia.\n* Meet minimum investment or turnover thresholds, depending on the visa category.\n* Hold a Business Innovation and Investment Visa or Investor Visa.\n\n**4. Employer Sponsorship**\n\n* Obtain sponsorship from an Australian employer.\n* Apply for a temporary employer-sponsored visa, such as subclass 482 or 494.\n* Meet eligibility criteria and work requirements.\n* Transition to permanent residency after meeting the required period of work in Australia.\n\n**5. Humanitarian Program**\n\n* Be granted asylum or humanitarian entry into Australia.\n* Meet the criteria for protection under the Refugee Convention or Convention Against Torture.\n* Apply for a Protection Visa or Humanitarian Visa.\n\n**General Requirements**\n\n* Meet health and character requirements.\n* Pass English language proficiency tests, if required for the visa category.\n* Have sufficient funds to support yourself and any dependents in Australia.\n* Be of good health and character.\n\n**Steps to Apply**\n\n* Research and choose a pathway that suits your circumstances.\n* Gather all necessary documents and meet the eligibility criteria.\n* Lodge your application online or through an authorized agent.\n* Pay the application fee.\n* Wait for processing times to vary depending on the visa category.\n\n**Additional Resources**\n\n* [Department of Home Affairs: Permanent Residence Visas](https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/permanent-residence)\n* [Australian Government: Visas for Australia](https://www.australia.gov.au/information-and-services/immigration-and-asylum/visas-and-immigration)\n* [Migration Agents Registration Authority (MARA)](https://www.mara.gov.au/)',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 13:09:39',	0,	'2024-07-30 13:09:39',	0,	NULL),
(77,	0,	1,	20240730,	'ask',	'what are the subclass options of permanent resident visas for Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 13:10:37',	0,	'2024-07-30 13:10:37',	0,	NULL),
(78,	0,	1,	20240730,	'ask',	'what are the subclass options of permanent resident visas for Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 15:10:15',	0,	'2024-07-30 15:10:15',	0,	NULL),
(79,	78,	1,	20240730,	'reply',	'**Subclass 100: Parent Visa**\n\n* For parents of Australian citizens or permanent residents who wish to live in Australia.\n\n**Subclass 101: Contributory Parent (Temporary) Visa**\n\n* A four-year temporary visa for parents who meet certain income and financial requirements.\n\n**Subclass 102: Contributory Parent (Aged) Visa**\n\n* For parents aged 65 or older who have a child who is an Australian citizen or permanent resident.\n\n**Subclass 103: Contributory Parent (Balance of Family) Visa**\n\n* For parents who have children in Australia who are Australian citizens or permanent residents, and who have specific family balance considerations.\n\n**Subclass 104: Partner Provisional (Subclass 309) Visa**\n\n* For partners who are in a relationship with an Australian citizen or permanent resident, and who wish to live in Australia.\n\n**Subclass 105: Partner (Subclass 820) Visa**\n\n* For partners who have been in a relationship with an Australian citizen or permanent resident for at least 12 months, and who wish to live in Australia.\n\n**Subclass 112: Occupation List Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have been nominated by an Australian employer, and whose occupation is in high demand in Australia.\n\n**Subclass 113: Regional Sponsored Migration Scheme (RSMS) Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have been sponsored by an employer in a regional area of Australia.\n\n**Subclass 115: General Skilled Migration Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who meet certain skill and eligibility requirements, and who are invited to apply by the Australian government.\n\n**Subclass 116: Employer Nomination Scheme Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have been nominated by an Australian employer, and whose occupation is on the medium and long-term Strategic Skills List.\n\n**Subclass 117: Skilled Independent Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have not been nominated by an employer, but who meet certain skill and eligibility requirements.\n\n**Subclass 120: Business Long-Term Visa**\n\n* For individuals who have established or invested in a business in Australia.\n\n**Subclass 121: Business Visitor (Class EV) Visa**\n\n* For individuals who wish to come to Australia for business purposes, including investing, establishing or developing contacts.\n\n**Subclass 123: Significant Economic Contribution (Provisional) (Business Innovation) Visa**\n\n* For individuals who have made or intend to make a significant economic contribution to Australia through exceptional entrepreneurial skills.\n\n**Subclass 124: Significant Economic Contribution (Permanent) (Business Innovation) Visa**\n\n* For individuals who have successfully established and operated a business in Australia and have made a significant economic contribution.\n\n**Subclass 132: Business Innovation and Investment (Provisional) Visa**\n\n* For individuals who have innovative business concepts and intend to establish or invest in a business in Australia.\n\n**Subclass 133: Business Innovation and Investment (Permanent) Visa**\n\n* For individuals who have successfully established and operated their business in Australia and meet certain turnover and investment thresholds.\n\n**Subclass 143: Skilled Nominated (SC 491) Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have been nominated by an Australian state or territory government, and whose occupation is in high demand in that state or territory.\n\n**Subclass 186: Employer Nomination Scheme (Temporary) Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have been nominated by an Australian employer, and whose occupation is on the Short-Term Skilled Occupation List.\n\n**Subclass 187: Regional Sponsored Migration Scheme (Provisional) Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have been sponsored by an employer in a regional area of Australia, and whose occupation is on the Medium and Long-Term Strategic Skills List.\n\n**Subclass 188: Skilled Independent Visa (Subclass 189) Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have not been nominated by an employer, but who meet certain skill and eligibility requirements, and have received an invitation to apply.\n\n**Subclass 189: Skilled Nominated (Class VK) Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have been nominated by an Australian state or territory government, and who meet certain skill and eligibility requirements.\n\n**Subclass 190: Business Innovation and Investment Visa**\n\n* For individuals who have innovative business concepts and intend to establish or invest in a business in Australia.\n\n**Subclass 191: Skilled Regional (Provisional) Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have been sponsored by an employer in a regional area of Australia, and whose occupation is on the Medium and Long-Term Strategic Skills List.\n\n**Subclass 192: Skilled Regional (Permanent) Visa**\n\n* For skilled workers who have successfully lived and worked in a regional area of Australia for three years on a Skilled Regional (Provisional) Visa.\n\n**Subclass 200: Skilled Independent (Child) Visa**\n\n* For children under the age of 18 who are dependants of the primary applicant on a Skilled Independent Visa.\n\n**Subclass 201: Skilled Nominated (Subclass 190) Visa**\n\n* For children under the age of 18 who are dependants of the primary applicant on a Skilled Nominated (Subclass 190) Visa.\n\n**Subclass 202: Skilled Regional (Provisional) Visa**\n\n* For children under the age of 18 who are dependants of the primary applicant on a Skilled Regional (Provisional) Visa.\n\n**Subclass 203: Skilled Regional (Permanent) Visa**\n\n* For children under the age of 18 who are dependants of the primary applicant on a Skilled Regional (Permanent) Visa.\n\n**Subclass 205: Child of Skill Migrant (Subclass 491) Visa**\n\n* For children under the age of 18 who are dependants of the primary applicant on a Skilled Nominated (Subclass 491) Visa.',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 15:10:15',	0,	'2024-07-30 15:10:15',	0,	NULL),
(80,	0,	1,	20240730,	'ask',	'what are the requirements for global talent visa of Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 15:11:42',	0,	'2024-07-30 15:11:42',	0,	NULL),
(81,	80,	1,	20240730,	'reply',	'**Eligibility Requirements**\n\n* **Occupation:** Must hold an eligible occupation as listed on the Skilled Occupation List (SOL).\n* **Skills:** Meet the required skill level and experience for the nominated occupation.\n* **Age:** Under 45 years of age (exceptions apply for certain occupations).\n* **English proficiency:** Demonstrate a high level of English proficiency equivalent to IELTS 7+ in all four language skills (speaking, listening, reading, writing).\n* **Exceptional talent:** Evidence of exceptional and outstanding skills, expertise, or achievements in a field of global significance.\n* **Endorsement:** Receive an endorsement from an Australian state or territory government, or a Global Talent Service Provider.\n\n**Nomination Requirements**\n\n* **Occupation:** Must be nominated by an eligible employer in Australia.\n* **Support:** Employer must provide evidence of support, including job offer, salary details, and intended work location.\n* **Skills:** Employer must confirm that the applicant&#039;s skills and experience meet the requirements for the nominated occupation.\n* **Market Salary:** Employer must demonstrate that the offered salary meets or exceeds the market salary rate for the nominated occupation.\n* **Intentions:** Applicant must provide clear evidence of their intention to work in Australia for the duration of the visa.\n\n**Additional Requirements**\n\n* **Health:** Pass a health examination.\n* **Character:** Clear criminal record.\n* **Documents:** Provide supporting documents to evidence all claims and requirements.\n* **Fees:** Pay the relevant visa application and nomination fees.\n\n**Priority Processing**\n\n* Priority processing is available for eligible applicants who can demonstrate a significant contribution to Australia&#039;s economy, innovation, or culture.\n* Applicants must meet additional criteria, such as:\n    * Exceptional talent in a field of national significance.\n    * Potential to create significant economic or social impact.\n    * Endorsement from a reputable organization or individual.',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 15:11:42',	0,	'2024-07-30 15:11:42',	0,	NULL),
(82,	0,	1,	20240730,	'ask',	'how can I apply for a working holiday visa in Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 16:38:52',	0,	'2024-07-30 16:38:52',	0,	NULL),
(83,	82,	1,	20240730,	'reply',	'**Eligibility Requirements:**\n\n* Be a citizen of an eligible country (check the Australian government&#039;s website)\n* Be aged between 18 and 30 (35 for Canadian and Irish citizens)\n* Hold a valid passport with at least 6 months validity beyond your intended stay\n* Have sufficient funds to support yourself during your stay\n* Have a return ticket or sufficient funds to purchase one\n* Not have been previously granted a Working Holiday (subclass 417) visa\n\n**Application Process:**\n\n1. **Create an ImmiAccount:** Go to the Australian government&#039;s immigration website (immi.homeaffairs.gov.au) and create an account.\n2. **Complete the online application form (Subclass 417):** Provide personal details, travel plans, and other relevant information.\n3. **Attach required supporting documents:** These may include:\n    * Proof of identity (e.g., passport)\n    * Proof of funds (e.g., bank statements)\n    * Letter of intent explaining why you want to work and holiday in Australia\n    * Certificate of health\n    * Police clearance certificate (if required)\n4. **Pay the application fee:** The fee varies depending on your nationality.\n5. **Submit your application:** Review your application carefully and click &quot;submit&quot;.\n\n**After Submission:**\n\n* You will receive an acknowledgment email.\n* Your application will be assessed by the Australian Department of Home Affairs.\n* You will be notified if further information is required.\n* If your application is successful, you will receive an email with instructions on how to apply for the visa grant.\n\n**Visa Grant Process:**\n\n* Attend a biometrics appointment (if required).\n* Pay the visa grant fee.\n* Your visa will be activated once these steps are complete.\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n* Start your application early as processing times can vary.\n* Ensure your application is complete and accurate.\n* Consider using a migration agent for assistance if needed.\n* Visit the Australian government&#039;s website for the most up-to-date information on eligibility and application requirements.',	1,	0,	'2024-07-30 16:38:52',	0,	'2024-07-30 16:38:52',	0,	NULL),
(84,	0,	13,	20240809,	'ask',	'自動表格填寫',	1,	0,	'2024-08-09 12:29:47',	0,	'2024-08-09 12:29:47',	0,	NULL),
(85,	84,	13,	20240809,	'reply',	'**自動表格填寫**\n\n**定義：**\n\n使用軟體或工具自動完成表格中資料輸入的過程。\n\n**好處：**\n\n* **省時：**大幅減少手動輸入資料所需的時間。\n* **提高準確度：**自動化流程有助於減少錯誤。\n* **提高效率：**簡化任務，使員工可以專注於更有價值的工作。\n* **消除重複：**重複輸入相同資料的情況減少。\n\n**方法：**\n\n有幾種方法可以自動填寫表格：\n\n* **表格處理軟體：**例如 Microsoft Excel 或 Google Sheets，這些軟體具有自動填寫功能，例如自動完成、條件格式化和巨集。\n* **瀏覽器擴充功能：**例如 RoboForm、LastPass 或 Dashlane，這些擴充功能可以儲存表格資料並自動填寫。\n* **自動填寫服務：**例如 Autofill 和 Roboform，這些服務與網站整合，自動填寫表格資料。\n* **光學字元辨識 (OCR) 技術：**使用 OCR 技術的軟體可以掃描紙本表格，將資料轉換為數位格式，並自動填寫電子表格。\n* **人工智慧 (AI)：**AI 技術的進步，例如自然語言處理 (NLP)，使軟體可以理解表格結構並自動填寫資料。\n\n**應用：**\n\n自動表格填寫可用於各種應用程式中，包括：\n\n* **客户關係管理 (CRM)：**自動填寫連絡人資料、銷售機會和支援案件。\n* **電子商務：**快速填寫購物車資訊、結帳地址和付款細節。\n* **員工管理：**自動化員工資訊、時數表和薪資的輸入。\n* **金融業務：**自動填寫貸款申請表、轉帳令和報稅文件。\n* **醫療保健：**輸入病歷、處方和保險資訊。\n\n**實施注意事項：**\n\n實施自動表格填寫時，應考慮以下注意事項：\n\n* **資料準確度：**確保自動填寫的資料準確且最新。\n* **安全性：**保護敏感表格資料的安全性。\n* **可用性：**確保自動填寫功能在所有平台和設備上都能使用。\n* **法規遵循：**確保自動填寫過程符合法規要求。\n* **支援：**實作自動填寫系統時提供適當的支援。',	1,	0,	'2024-08-09 12:29:47',	0,	'2024-08-09 12:29:47',	0,	NULL),
(86,	0,	1,	20240813,	'ask',	'How can I move to Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-08-13 10:17:45',	0,	'2024-08-13 10:17:45',	0,	NULL),
(87,	86,	1,	20240813,	'reply',	'**Eligibility Requirements:**\n\n* **Age:** Most visa categories have an upper age limit of 45.\n* **Occupation:** Australia targets skilled migrants in high-demand occupations.\n* **English Language Proficiency:** A minimum score on IELTS, OET, or PTE tests is required.\n* **Health:** You must meet certain health standards and undergo medical examinations.\n* **Character:** You must have a clean criminal record.\n\n**Visa Options:**\n\n* **Skilled Independent Visa (Subclass 189):** For skilled workers with an occupation on the Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL).\n* **Skilled Nominated Visa (Subclass 190):** For skilled workers sponsored by an Australian state or territory.\n* **Employer Sponsored Visa (Subclass 482):** For workers employed by an Australian employer.\n* **Business Innovation and Investment Visa (Subclass 188):** For individuals seeking to establish or invest in a business in Australia.\n\n**Application Process:**\n\n1. **Skill Assessment:** Your occupation must be assessed and recognized by an Australian skills assessing authority.\n2. **EOI (Expression of Interest):** Lodge an EOI in the relevant visa category and wait for an invitation to apply.\n3. **Visa Application:** Submit a visa application with supporting documents such as proof of skills, employment, and English proficiency.\n4. **Medical and Character Checks:** Undergo medical examinations and provide police clearance certificates.\n\n**Additional Pathways:**\n\n* **Partner Visa:** If you have a spouse or de facto partner who is an Australian citizen or permanent resident.\n* **Student Visa:** If you wish to study in Australia and transition to a work visa later.\n* **Refugee Visa:** If you are seeking asylum due to persecution or fear of harm.\n\n**Tips:**\n\n* **Research your options thoroughly:** Explore different visa categories and determine which one aligns with your skills and circumstances.\n* **Prepare your application carefully:** Gather all necessary documents and ensure they meet the required standards.\n* **Seek professional advice:** Consult with a registered migration agent or lawyer for guidance throughout the process.\n* **Be patient:** The visa application process can take several months or even years.\n* **Consider state sponsorship:** Some states may offer faster visa processing pathways or provide additional support for skilled migrants.',	1,	0,	'2024-08-13 10:17:45',	0,	'2024-08-13 10:17:45',	0,	NULL),
(88,	0,	1,	20240813,	'ask',	'How can I migrate to Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-08-13 10:22:47',	0,	'2024-08-13 10:22:47',	0,	NULL),
(89,	88,	1,	20240813,	'reply',	'**Eligibility Criteria:**\n\n* Meet the minimum age requirement (usually 18)\n* Have a valid passport\n* Hold a skilled occupation on Australia&#039;s Skilled Occupation List (SOL) or be sponsored by a family member or employer\n\n**Visa Options:**\n\n**Independent Skilled Migration:**\n\n* Skilled Independent Visa (Subclass 189): Permanent residency without sponsorship\n* Skilled Nominated Visa (Subclass 190): Permanent residency with nomination by a state or territory\n\n**Employer-Sponsored Migration:**\n\n* Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS): Visa for skilled workers sponsored by an Australian employer\n* Regional Sponsored Migration Scheme (RSMS): Visa for skilled workers sponsored by an employer in a regional area\n\n**Family-Sponsored Migration:**\n\n* Parent Visa (Subclass 103): Permanent residency for parents of Australian citizens or permanent residents\n* Partner Visa (Subclass 309/100): Visa for spouses or de facto partners of Australian citizens or permanent residents\n\n**Application Process:**\n\n**1. Skill Assessment:**\n* Obtain a positive skill assessment from an Australian assessing authority for your occupation (e.g., Engineers Australia, Nursing and Midwifery Board of Australia).\n\n**2. Expression of Interest (EOI):**\n* Create an EOI in SkillSelect, the online application system for skilled migration.\n\n**3. Invitation to Apply:**\n* If you are invited to apply, you will be given 60 days to submit a complete visa application.\n\n**4. Visa Application:**\n* Gather all necessary supporting documentation, including:\n    * Proof of identity\n    * Skill assessment\n    * Language test results (if required)\n    * Police clearance certificates\n    * Financial documents\n\n**5. Visa Assessment:**\n* The Department of Home Affairs will assess your application and make a decision.\n\n**Additional Steps:**\n\n* **Medical Examination:** You may be required to undergo a medical examination.\n* **Security Check:** All applicants undergo a security check.\n* **Visa Grant:** If your visa is granted, you will receive a visa grant letter.\n* **Relocation:** You can then prepare for your move to Australia.\n\n**Resources:**\n\n* [Department of Home Affairs](https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/)\n* [SkillSelect](https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/working-in-australia/skill-select)\n* [Skilled Occupation List (SOL)](https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/working-in-australia/skill-occupation-list)',	1,	0,	'2024-08-13 10:22:47',	0,	'2024-08-13 10:22:47',	0,	NULL),
(90,	0,	1,	20240813,	'ask',	'How can I migrate to Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-08-13 10:36:10',	0,	'2024-08-13 10:36:10',	0,	NULL),
(91,	90,	1,	20240813,	'reply',	'**Step 1: Determine Eligibility**\n\n* Check if you meet the requirements for an Australian visa category: https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas\n\n**Step 2: Choose a Visa Category**\n\n* Based on your eligibility, select the appropriate visa category that aligns with your reasons for migrating, such as skilled worker, student, or family reunification.\n\n**Step 3: Submit an Expression of Interest (EOI)**\n\n* For certain visas (e.g., Skilled Independent Visa), you need to submit an EOI through SkillSelect: https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/getting-a-visa/skilled-visas/skillselect\n\n**Step 4: Obtain a Skill Assessment (if applicable)**\n\n* For many skilled visas, you need to have your skills assessed by an authorized body: https://www.talent.gov.au/toolkits/overseas-skilled-workers/skills-assessment-information\n\n**Step 5: Apply for the Visa**\n\n* Gather the required documents and submit a formal visa application through the Department of Home Affairs website: https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/getting-a-visa\n\n**Step 6: Document Submission**\n\n* Provide all necessary supporting documents, including proof of identity, skills, and financial means.\n\n**Step 7: Medical and Character Checks**\n\n* You may be required to undergo medical examinations and provide police clearances for character verification.\n\n**Step 8: Visa Processing**\n\n* The visa application will be processed and assessed by the Department of Home Affairs. This can take several months.\n\n**Step 9: Visa Grant**\n\n* If your visa application is successful, you will be granted an Australian visa.\n\n**Additional Resources:**\n\n* Department of Home Affairs: https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/\n* SkillSelect: https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/getting-a-visa/skilled-visas/skillselect\n* Australian Skills Recognition Information Service: https://www.asris.com.au/\n* Migration Agents Registration Authority (MARA): https://www.mara.gov.au/\n\n**Tips:**\n\n* Start the process early as it can take significant time.\n* Gather all necessary documents and provide accurate information.\n* Seek professional advice from a registered migration agent if necessary.\n* Be patient and follow the instructions carefully.',	1,	0,	'2024-08-13 10:36:10',	0,	'2024-08-13 10:36:10',	0,	NULL),
(92,	0,	1,	20240815,	'ask',	'How do I start',	1,	0,	'2024-08-15 08:33:00',	0,	'2024-08-15 08:33:00',	0,	NULL),
(93,	92,	1,	20240815,	'reply',	'**1. Define Your Purpose and Goals:**\n\n* Identify the problem or opportunity you aim to address.\n* Determine specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-bound (SMART) goals.\n* Articulate your mission, vision, and values.\n\n**2. Conduct Research and Gather Information:**\n\n* Collect data on your target audience, market, and competition.\n* Analyze existing solutions to identify strengths, weaknesses, and opportunities.\n* Seek feedback from potential users or stakeholders.\n\n**3. Develop Your Solution:**\n\n* Brainstorm and generate ideas for potential solutions.\n* Explore different approaches and technologies.\n* Prototype or test your solutions to validate their effectiveness.\n\n**4. Build Your Team:**\n\n* Identify the skills and expertise needed for your project.\n* Recruit and assemble a team of talented individuals.\n* Define roles and responsibilities for each team member.\n\n**5. Secure Funding (if necessary):**\n\n* Determine the financial resources required to implement your solution.\n* Explore funding options such as grants, investments, or crowdfunding.\n* Prepare a compelling pitch to present to potential investors.\n\n**6. Launch Your Solution:**\n\n* Prepare for market entry by developing a launch strategy.\n* Promote your solution through marketing and outreach campaigns.\n* Monitor and evaluate results to make necessary adjustments.\n\n**7. Iteratively Improve and Scale:**\n\n* Gather feedback from users and stakeholders to identify areas for improvement.\n* Update and enhance your solution based on feedback.\n* Explore opportunities for scaling your solution to reach a wider audience.\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n* **Start small:** Begin with a manageable project that you can complete successfully.\n* **Be adaptable:** Embrace change and be willing to adjust your plans as needed.\n* **Collaborate:** Seek input and partnerships from others throughout the process.\n* **Stay organized:** Use tools and techniques to manage your project and track progress.\n* **Celebrate successes:** Recognize and reward achievements along the way to maintain motivation.',	1,	0,	'2024-08-15 08:33:00',	0,	'2024-08-15 08:33:00',	0,	NULL),
(94,	0,	1,	20240815,	'ask',	'How do I start, frame answer in context off migration Canada',	1,	0,	'2024-08-15 08:47:29',	0,	'2024-08-15 08:47:29',	0,	NULL),
(95,	94,	1,	20240815,	'reply',	'**How to Start the Immigration Process to Canada**\n\n**1. Determine Eligibility**\n\n* Visit the official Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship Canada (IRCC) website: https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship.html\n* Explore various immigration programs and identify the one that aligns with your skills, experience, and goals.\n* Use the online eligibility self-assessment tools to check your potential.\n\n**2. Gather Required Documents**\n\n* Collect official documents such as passports, educational certificates, proof of employment, and other relevant materials.\n* Ensure documents are translated into English or French (if not already in these languages).\n* Notarize or certify copies of documents as required.\n\n**3. Create an Express Entry Profile (if applicable)**\n\n* For certain economic immigration programs (e.g., Federal Skilled Worker), you need to create an Express Entry profile.\n* This profile contains your personal information, education, work experience, and language abilities.\n* It assigns you a Comprehensive Ranking System (CRS) score based on your qualifications.\n\n**4. Submit an Application**\n\n* Once you&#039;re eligible and have created an Express Entry profile (if applicable), apply online through the IRCC website.\n* Provide all necessary information and supporting documents.\n* Pay the required application fees.\n\n**5. Wait for Processing**\n\n* IRCC will process your application and assess your eligibility against the criteria of the program you applied under.\n* Processing times vary depending on the program and applicant&#039;s individual circumstances.\n\n**6. Decision and Next Steps**\n\n* If you meet the eligibility requirements, you may receive an Invitation to Apply (ITA).\n* You will then need to submit a complete application, including additional documents and any medical or biometrics exams required.\n* Once your application is approved, you&#039;ll be issued a Confirmation of Permanent Residence (COPR) and will be able to enter Canada as a permanent resident.',	1,	0,	'2024-08-15 08:47:29',	0,	'2024-08-15 08:47:29',	0,	NULL),
(96,	0,	1,	20240815,	'ask',	'How to move to Australia?',	1,	0,	'2024-08-15 11:24:13',	0,	'2024-08-15 11:24:13',	0,	NULL),
(97,	96,	1,	20240815,	'reply',	'**Eligibility and Requirements:**\n\n* **Skilled Migration Visa:** This is the most common pathway for skilled workers. You must have a skilled occupation on the Skilled Occupation List (SOL) and meet the minimum points threshold (65 points).\n* **Employer Nomination Scheme:** If you have a job offer from an Australian employer, you can apply for this visa.\n* **Family Sponsored Visa:** If you have family members who are Australian citizens or permanent residents, you may be eligible for a family-sponsored visa.\n\n**Steps to Move to Australia:**\n\n**1. Identify an Eligible Visa:** Determine which visa pathway is most suitable for your situation.\n\n**2. Gather Supporting Documents:** Collect all necessary documentation, such as your passport, work experience, educational qualifications, and language proficiency test results.\n\n**3. Apply for the Visa:** Submit your visa application and pay the application fee. Make sure to provide all required information and supporting documents.\n\n**4. Skill Assessment:** For skilled migration visas, you will need to get your skills assessed by an Australian assessing authority.\n\n**5. Points Test:** If applying for a skilled migration visa, you will need to calculate your points under the points test system.\n\n**6. Invitation to Apply:** If you meet the minimum points threshold, you may receive an Invitation to Apply (ITA) for a visa.\n\n**7. Visa Processing:** Submit your complete visa application with all supporting documents. The processing time varies depending on the visa type and circumstances.\n\n**8. Medical Examination:** You may be required to undergo a medical examination as part of the visa process.\n\n**9. Biometrics:** You will need to provide your biometrics (fingerprints and photo) for certain visa applications.\n\n**10. Visa Grant:** If your visa is approved, you will receive a visa grant.\n\n**11. Arrive in Australia:** Make travel arrangements to Australia and present your visa upon arrival.\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n* Research your chosen visa pathway thoroughly.\n* Seek professional advice from an immigration agent or lawyer if needed.\n* Make sure you meet all eligibility requirements.\n* Gather all necessary documentation well in advance.\n* Be patient, as the visa process can take time.\n* Consider learning about Australian culture and customs before arriving.',	1,	0,	'2024-08-15 11:24:13',	0,	'2024-08-15 11:24:13',	0,	NULL),
